00:08:24.270 --> 00:08:26.190
Turns out if you take
two brushless motors,

00:08:26.190 --> 00:08:28.260
two electronic motor speed controllers,

00:08:28.260 --> 00:08:30.690
a flight controller that
actually has a gyroscope

00:08:30.690 --> 00:08:32.460
and an accelerometer integrated,

00:08:32.460 --> 00:08:36.150
a 3D-printed frame, and two
servos to articulate the rotors,

00:08:36.150 --> 00:08:38.280
a radio transmitter for a remote control,

00:08:38.280 --> 00:08:39.990
and a four-cell lipo battery,

00:08:39.990 --> 00:08:41.670
and then you put them all together,

00:08:41.670 --> 00:08:42.503
it actually works.

00:08:42.503 --> 00:08:43.336
(propeller whining)

00:08:43.336 --> 00:08:44.190
(machine clattering)

00:08:44.190 --> 00:08:45.060
Kind of.

00:08:45.060 --> 00:08:46.530
We had to do a bunch of test flights

00:08:46.530 --> 00:08:48.360
to calibrate that feedback control loop

00:08:48.360 --> 00:08:49.740
we talked about before.

00:08:49.740 --> 00:08:52.050
So if we notice the drone
is either undercompensated

00:08:52.050 --> 00:08:55.260
or overcompensating when it
